00:46:13.070 --> 00:46:16.110
That's coronagraphy,
a coronagraph,

00:46:16.110 --> 00:46:18.750
where you put something
in the light path

00:46:18.750 --> 00:46:22.050
to block out-- just like your
thumb-- block out the light.

00:46:22.050 --> 00:46:24.840
The problem is that stars
create this diffraction when

00:46:24.840 --> 00:46:27.950
they come into your telescope,
and you saw that, right?

00:46:27.950 --> 00:46:31.560
Now, there are technology
hurdles to accomplishing this.

00:46:31.560 --> 00:46:34.770
One, for example--
during that process,

00:46:34.770 --> 00:46:36.460
where you've got the
pistons, and you're

00:46:36.460 --> 00:46:37.950
adjusting the
shape of the mirror

00:46:37.950 --> 00:46:40.340
and making all of these
subtle corrections--

00:46:40.340 --> 00:46:43.320
during that process, you
need pointing stability down

00:46:43.320 --> 00:46:45.360
to like a picometer.

00:46:45.360 --> 00:46:47.640
Really, really exceptional
pointing stability.

00:46:47.640 --> 00:46:49.950
So that's one technology hurdle.

00:46:49.950 --> 00:46:53.160
Another technology hurdle
is that well, OK, fine--

00:46:53.160 --> 00:46:56.051
but you still need to
collect enough photons.

00:46:56.051 --> 00:46:57.550
These things are
really, really dim.

00:46:57.550 --> 00:47:00.020
I need a huge
photon bucket, which

00:47:00.020 --> 00:47:02.890
means a big, gigantic mirror.

00:47:02.890 --> 00:47:05.770
The only way we're going to get
a big, gigantic 10-meter dish

00:47:05.770 --> 00:47:09.320
mirror out into space is by
making it segmented and folding

00:47:09.320 --> 00:47:11.070
it up into your rocket ferry.

00:47:11.070 --> 00:47:11.880
Right?

00:47:11.880 --> 00:47:13.470
The problem is that
when you do that,

00:47:13.470 --> 00:47:15.130
when you make a
segmented mirror,

00:47:15.130 --> 00:47:18.710
all of that diffraction that
you saw that makes the rings

00:47:18.710 --> 00:47:20.230
is different.

00:47:20.230 --> 00:47:24.110
So we have to learn how to do
this with segmented mirrors.

00:47:24.110 --> 00:47:27.200
We have to learn how to
achieve that picometer

00:47:27.200 --> 00:47:30.441
stability in the pointing, in
the thermal sensitivity, all

00:47:30.441 --> 00:47:30.940
of that.

00:47:30.940 --> 00:47:33.230
It's really going
to be challenging.

00:47:33.230 --> 00:47:36.990
Now, you can simplify
that if you figure out

00:47:36.990 --> 00:47:40.820
a way to hold a giant thumb out
into space instead of putting

00:47:40.820 --> 00:47:43.400
it in your optical path.

00:47:43.400 --> 00:47:45.470
If I can put a giant
thumb out in space,

00:47:45.470 --> 00:47:47.180
it's going to make
it much more simple.

00:47:47.180 --> 00:47:48.920
I'm taking it out
of the optical path,

00:47:48.920 --> 00:47:51.870
and I don't have to worry
about that wavefront control.

00:47:51.870 --> 00:47:52.980
And we're trying that.

00:47:52.980 --> 00:47:54.880
This is called
starshade technology,

00:47:54.880 --> 00:47:58.050
and this is the next video.

00:47:58.050 --> 00:47:59.260
Here, there's no audio.

00:47:59.260 --> 00:48:03.340
What you're seeing is
a probe class starshade

00:48:03.340 --> 00:48:06.970
that is unfurling and
creating a shape that

00:48:06.970 --> 00:48:08.990
looks like a sunflower.

00:48:08.990 --> 00:48:12.760
It has that special sunflower
shape because of the way

00:48:12.760 --> 00:48:15.180
that we want it to
control diffraction.

00:48:15.180 --> 00:48:17.000
But the idea is
that you're going

00:48:17.000 --> 00:48:20.130
to fly this thing independently
some tens of thousands

00:48:20.130 --> 00:48:23.290
of kilometers away, so
that it gets really tiny

00:48:23.290 --> 00:48:26.020
and perfectly blocks
out the starlight.

00:48:26.020 --> 00:48:28.360
You're going to have
another space telescope that

00:48:28.360 --> 00:48:32.010
