metrology to communicate

00:48:32.010 --> 00:48:35.420
with the starshade and get it
perfectly pointed and aligned,

00:48:35.420 --> 00:48:39.420
and hold it there, steady--
like a giant thumb up in space--

00:48:39.420 --> 00:48:43.284
so that you can see the
planets it lost in the glare.

00:48:43.284 --> 00:48:45.700
Two different technologies
that each have their advantages

00:48:45.700 --> 00:48:47.410
and disadvantages.

00:48:47.410 --> 00:48:49.300
The disadvantage of
this one, although it

00:48:49.300 --> 00:48:52.730
made the optics really
simple-- much more simple--

00:48:52.730 --> 00:48:56.250
the problem is that it's tens
of thousands of kilometers away,

00:48:56.250 --> 00:48:58.360
and now you want to
point over there and look

00:48:58.360 --> 00:49:00.180
for a planet over
there, and you've

00:49:00.180 --> 00:49:05.520
got to sit there and wait while
the starshade makes the journey

00:49:05.520 --> 00:49:07.120
from one place to another.

00:49:07.120 --> 00:49:09.920
So you lose a lot of time.

00:49:09.920 --> 00:49:13.940
But if the telescope can stay
observing something else--

00:49:13.940 --> 00:49:17.090
making other astrophysics
contributions

00:49:17.090 --> 00:49:19.490
while you're waiting
for that slew time--

00:49:19.490 --> 00:49:21.680
