00:52:43.045 --> 00:52:47.050
that are emitted by complex
life forms on planet Earth

00:52:47.050 --> 00:52:51.590
as they metabolize food into
energy-- things like methane,

00:52:51.590 --> 00:52:55.270
oxygen, respiration
processes, all of those things

00:52:55.270 --> 00:52:57.700
that are indication
not just of a planet

00:52:57.700 --> 00:53:00.370
but of an actual living world.

00:53:00.370 --> 00:53:01.920
Again, this is possible.

00:53:01.920 --> 00:53:04.080
It's not limited
by what we know,

00:53:04.080 --> 00:53:08.230
it's not limited by technology--
it's just simply limited

00:53:08.230 --> 00:53:09.010
by resources.

00:53:09.010 --> 00:53:11.980
So with enough time, we
will accomplish this.

00:53:11.980 --> 00:53:13.920
Could be maybe not
in my lifetime,

00:53:13.920 --> 00:53:16.940
but certainly in my children
or grandchildren's lifetime,

00:53:16.940 --> 00:53:19.060
I think that this is
going to happen-- where

00:53:19.060 --> 00:53:23.390
one day, soon, we will know for
certain that life does or does

00:53:23.390 --> 00:53:26.200
not exist beyond Earth.

00:53:26.200 --> 00:53:28.280
So that's where we're headed.

00:53:28.280 --> 00:53:33.380
And I'll end with the
beautiful retro travel posters

00:53:33.380 --> 00:53:38.000
that JPL created for these
worlds of our imagination

00:53:38.000 --> 00:53:44.300
that actually do exist, just
with quite not so much color.

00:53:44.300 --> 00:53:45.379
Yet.

00:53:45.379 --> 00:53:46.670
All right, thank you very much.

00:53:46.670 --> 00:53:47.961
I'd be happy to take questions.

00:53:47.961 --> 00:53:50.145
[APPLAUSE]

00:53:53.530 --> 00:53:54.992
AUDIENCE: I recently
read that you

00:53:54.992 --> 00:53:59.910
should be able to detect the
glare of a water-covered planet

00:53:59.910 --> 00:54:04.310
going in front of the star
that they orbit around.

00:54:04.310 --> 00:54:07.980
Would Kepler be able to see
this, or any of the satellites

00:54:07.980 --> 00:54:10.340
that are proposed?

00:54:10.340 --> 00:54:13.030
NATALIE BATALHA: So
to detect the glare--

00:54:13.030 --> 00:54:15.770
so when you say glare,
to me you're implying

00:54:15.770 --> 00:54:17.160
reflected light.

00:54:17.160 --> 00:54:18.840
So light that's
coming from the star

00:54:18.840 --> 00:54:21.710
is bouncing off of a
shiny surface right?

00:54:21.710 --> 00:54:23.280
And we see that.

00:54:23.280 --> 00:54:27.690
And so the question is, is
that possible with Kepler?

00:54:27.690 --> 00:54:34.970
We do see some phase functions
as planets are orbiting around.

00:54:34.970 --> 00:54:38.500
The kind of specular reflection
that you're talking about

00:54:38.500 --> 00:54:41.920
would happen at precise moments.

00:54:41.920 --> 00:54:45.090
We see these kinds
of phase functions

00:54:45.090 --> 00:54:48.390
for mostly giant planets
that are heated on one side

00:54:48.390 --> 00:54:53.160
compared to the other,
so I don't know.

00:54:53.160 --> 00:54:58.200
I'm not aware of any
such a detection.

00:54:58.200 --> 00:55:00.020
We will do this in the future.

00:55:00.020 --> 00:55:03.260
I think that our best bet
is to do the transmission

00:55:03.260 --> 00:55:06.500
spectroscopy between
TESS and JWST,

00:55:06.500 --> 00:55:08.301
see the light come
through the atmosphere--

00:55:08.301 --> 00:55:09.800
so you're not talking
about a glare,

00:55:09.800 --> 00:55:12.130
you're talking
about transmission--

00:55:12.130 --> 00:55:16.790
and hopefully see
evidence of water vapor.

00:55:16.790 --> 00:55:19.370
Whether or not we'll have
the kind of situation--

00:55:19.370 --> 00:55:22.830
I'm not even sure water
worlds exist in entirety,

00:55:22.830 --> 00:55:27.076
but certainly oceans-- the
kind of specular reflection

00:55:27.076 --> 00:55:29.450
that happens quickly when
you're just at the right angle,

00:55:29.450 --> 00:55:32.310
I think, is going to be
very difficult to find.

00:55:32.310 --> 00:55:32.890
Yeah.

00:55:32.890 --> 00:55:34.870
Just thinking out loud here.

00:55:34.870 --> 00:55:36.980
AUDIENCE: Direct
imaging-- is it easier

00:55:36.980 --> 00:55:40.010
to just do the reflected
light from the star,

00:55:40.010 --> 00:55:42.340
or the transmission
from the planet

00:55:42.340 --> 00:55:43.477
based on its temperature?

00:55:43.477 --> 00:55:44.310
NATALIE BATALHA: OK.

00:55:44.310 --> 00:55:47.167
So the direct image emissions
are reflected light off

00:55:47.167 --> 00:55:48.750
of the surface, but
they can also be--

00:55:48.750 --> 00:55:49.680
and this is where
I thought you were

00:55:49.680 --> 00:55:52.520
going with that question-- they
can also be thermal emission.

00:55:52.520 --> 00:55:54.600
That is, the warmth
of the planet

00:55:54.600 --> 00:55:58.300
itself-- like in the case
of the multi-planet system

00:55:58.300 --> 00:55:59.730
from direct imaging
that you saw--

00:55:59.730 --> 00:56:02.080
that was enabled by the
fact that the planets are

00:56:02.080 --> 00:56:04.710
young and hot, so they're
emitting thermal radiation

00:56:04.710 --> 00:56:06.470
and you're seeing
that emission as well.

00:56:06.470 --> 00:56:08.350
AUDIENCE: Well, and the contrast
between the star and the planet

00:56:08.350 --> 00:56:10.410
would vary based on which
wavelength you're looking at--

00:56:10.410 --> 00:56:10.560
NATALIE BATALHA: Absolutely.

00:56:10.560 --> 00:56:10.905
That's right.

00:56:10.905 --> 00:56:12.090
AUDIENCE: --and based
on the temperature, too.

00:56:12.090 --> 00:56:12.670
NATALIE BATALHA: That's correct.

00:56:12.670 --> 00:56:14.086
AUDIENCE: So if
it would be easier

00:56:14.086 --> 00:56:16.480
to look for really hot
planets close in because--

00:56:16.480 --> 00:56:16.648
NATALIE BATALHA: Ah.

00:56:16.648 --> 00:56:16.760
I see.

00:56:16.760 --> 00:56:18.634
AUDIENCE: They're emitting
a radiation length

00:56:18.634 --> 00:56:20.960
that the star doesn't emit
at as much as it normally--

00:56:20.960 --> 00:56:23.340
NATALIE BATALHA: Yeah, but
see, when they're close in,

00:56:23.340 --> 00:56:25.510
you have a resolution problem.

00:56:25.510 --> 00:56:28.017
One of the other reasons why
you need a big telescope even

00:56:28.017 --> 00:56:29.850
to see the Goldilocks
Zone is because you're

00:56:29.850 --> 00:56:32.490
trying to separate-- you're
trying to be able to resolve

00:56:32.490 --> 00:56:34.580
a planet next to a star, right?

00:56:34.580 --> 00:56:37.730
And so resolution is
proportional to the diameter

00:56:37.730 --> 00:56:38.870
of the telescope.

00:56:38.870 --> 00:56:41.470
So the closer in
you want to see,

00:56:41.470 --> 00:56:43.620
the higher resolution
you're going to need,

00:56:43.620 --> 00:56:45.810
and we're already really
hard-pressed to do that

00:56:45.810 --> 00:56:48.670
for an Earth out at 365 days.

00:56:48.670 --> 00:56:51.150
So if you want to do something
for planets that are even

00:56:51.150 --> 00:56:53.210
closer, you have two choices.

00:56:53.210 --> 00:56:55.064
Either you do
transmission spectroscopy

00:56:55.064 --> 00:56:56.480
in the way that
you've mentioned--

00:56:56.480 --> 00:56:59.830
but that, of course, only works
if you have the right geometry.

00:56:59.830 --> 00:57:02.020
Or the other
alternative-- and I think

00:57:02.020 --> 00:57:06.200
this is going to
happen-- on the ground,

00:57:06.200 --> 00:57:09.450
we are already building
30-meter telescopes, so

00:57:09.450 --> 00:57:12.860
telescopes that are three
times bigger in diameter,

00:57:12.860 --> 00:57:17.140
27 times more collecting area,
and you get the same benefit

00:57:17.140 --> 00:57:18.300
with resolution.

00:57:18.300 --> 00:57:20.860
So now you have the
possibility of seeing

00:57:20.860 --> 00:57:25.090
the habitable zone of the M-type
stars, which are closer in.

00:57:25.090 --> 00:57:27.370
You can't do that with a
10-meter class telescope

00:57:27.370 --> 00:57:29.807
even in space, because you
just don't have the resolution.

00:57:29.807 --> 00:57:31.890
But with the 30-meter
telescopes from the ground--

00:57:31.890 --> 00:57:34.306
if we can work out the rest
of the technology challenges--

00:57:34.306 --> 00:57:36.750
we might be able to do it.

00:57:36.750 --> 00:57:39.400
AUDIENCE: You mentioned
the orientation.

00:57:39.400 --> 00:57:41.150
Do you find that it's
typically consistent

00:57:41.150 --> 00:57:43.810
that we tend to be with
the disk of the galaxy,

00:57:43.810 --> 00:57:45.670
or are they pretty
randomly oriented?

00:57:45.670 --> 00:57:47.878
NATALIE BATALHA: Yeah, that's
a really good question.

00:57:47.878 --> 00:57:50.350
The question is, do we have
any preferential geometry

00:57:50.350 --> 00:57:54.010
in the galaxy with
these orbital planes?

00:57:54.010 --> 00:57:58.220
And the answer's no-- that
they're all cattywampus,

00:57:58.220 --> 00:58:00.850
randomly distributed.

00:58:00.850 --> 00:58:03.940
AUDIENCE: Would there be any
disadvantage, or advantage

00:58:03.940 --> 00:58:07.660
or disadvantage, to something,
a telescope based on the moon,

00:58:07.660 --> 00:58:09.670
so you have something
solid to put it on

00:58:09.670 --> 00:58:11.257
and still no atmosphere?

00:58:11.257 --> 00:58:12.840
NATALIE BATALHA: Is
there an advantage

00:58:12.840 --> 00:58:14.871
to building a
telescope on the moon?

00:58:14.871 --> 00:58:16.370
AUDIENCE: I'm
thinking like, instead

00:58:16.370 --> 00:58:19.390
of having to put a
satellite out far away,

00:58:19.390 --> 00:58:21.240
you might be able
to put a relatively

00:58:21.240 --> 00:58:24.580
small thing on a mountain
a few kilometers away.

00:58:24.580 --> 00:58:26.080
NATALIE BATALHA:
Yeah, which is kind

00:58:26.080 --> 00:58:28.663
of what we're doing on the Earth
to test the technology, where

00:58:28.663 --> 00:58:30.700
we're going out into the
desert and setting up

00:58:30.700 --> 00:58:32.899
systems like that.

00:58:32.899 --> 00:58:33.440
I don't know.

00:58:33.440 --> 00:58:34.820
That's a really good question.

00:58:34.820 --> 00:58:36.280
There are other
challenges you have

00:58:36.280 --> 00:58:38.270
to think about when you
go to the moon-- first

00:58:38.270 --> 00:58:40.176
of all, getting supplies there,
of course, because you're going

00:58:40.176 --> 00:58:41.870
to have to make multiple trips.

00:58:41.870 --> 00:58:44.530
But also the dynamics
on the moon--

00:58:44.530 --> 00:58:46.450
you've got a lot of dust, right?

00:58:46.450 --> 00:58:50.110
And so I know that one of the
biggest technological hurdles

00:58:50.110 --> 00:58:51.600
to building
telescopes on the moon

00:58:51.600 --> 00:58:53.490
is just the amount of dust.

00:58:53.490 --> 00:58:56.110
And we've got the regolith,
which has this very fine dust.

00:58:56.110 --> 00:58:58.850
In fact, if you do hiking
in California, because

00:58:58.850 --> 00:59:00.592
of the drought,
the ground-- God,

00:59:00.592 --> 00:59:02.550
I'd hiked up the
[? Ridge Lane ?] the other day

00:59:02.550 --> 00:59:05.090
for the eclipse, and it was
like I was walking on the moon.

00:59:05.090 --> 00:59:06.090
It was like, poof!

00:59:06.090 --> 00:59:07.090
Poof!

00:59:07.090 --> 00:59:08.940
So if you have even
lower surface gravity,

00:59:08.940 --> 00:59:10.570
that dust is going to loft.

00:59:10.570 --> 00:59:12.236
It's going to get
into your electronics.

00:59:12.236 --> 00:59:14.284
It's going to be a mess.

00:59:14.284 --> 00:59:15.570
So, yeah.

00:59:15.570 --> 00:59:17.710
Nobody seems to be thinking
seriously about that,

00:59:17.710 --> 00:59:19.520
but that doesn't
mean that it's--

00:59:19.520 --> 00:59:21.476
AUDIENCE: What's the
status of Kepler today?

00:59:21.476 --> 00:59:23.350
I know that with its
reaction wheels failing,

00:59:23.350 --> 00:59:24.415
but there was some
back up plan in mind.

00:59:24.415 --> 00:59:24.690
NATALIE BATALHA: Yeah.

00:59:24.690 --> 00:59:25.670
Thanks for asking that.

00:59:25.670 --> 00:59:29.470
Maybe I'll go ahead and
back up a little bit.

00:59:29.470 --> 00:59:31.890
So the question is, what is
the status of Kepler today?

00:59:38.580 --> 00:59:42.790
A few years ago-- sorry.

00:59:42.790 --> 00:59:44.256
This is not very
efficient, is it?

00:59:46.820 --> 00:59:48.750
Well, several years
ago, Kepler lost

00:59:48.750 --> 00:59:49.982
one of its reaction wheels.

00:59:49.982 --> 00:59:52.440
And so the reaction wheels are
these like gyroscope things,

00:59:52.440 --> 00:59:55.790
that-- there are three of
them, one for each axis--

00:59:55.790 --> 00:59:59.890
and they keep the telescope
pointing very stably.

00:59:59.890 --> 01:00:02.630
So there was some redundancy
built into the spacecraft--

01:00:02.630 --> 01:00:03.540
there were four.

01:00:03.540 --> 01:00:05.040
You only need three,
because there's

01:00:05.040 --> 01:00:07.650
three axes you can rotate about.

01:00:07.650 --> 01:00:09.580
And so we had four, we
had some redundancy.

01:00:09.580 --> 01:00:10.950
We lost one.

01:00:10.950 --> 01:00:12.597
No problem, we've got three.

01:00:12.597 --> 01:00:14.346
But then, a couple
years ago-- in fact, it

01:00:14.346 --> 01:00:16.846
was on my birthday-- I was just
about sitting at my birthday

01:00:16.846 --> 01:00:18.660
lunch, and I got
the phone call-- we

01:00:18.660 --> 01:00:21.030
lost a second reaction wheel.

01:00:21.030 --> 01:00:22.555
So now, we were
down to two-- that

01:00:22.555 --> 01:00:24.610
meant Kepler was
spinning about one axis.

01:00:24.610 --> 01:00:25.860
We had no control.

01:00:25.860 --> 01:00:26.800
OK?

01:00:26.800 --> 01:00:29.955
So for me, I was like,
well, OK, we already

01:00:29.955 --> 01:00:31.830
completed our baseline
mission-- we'd already

01:00:31.830 --> 01:00:33.430
collected four years
of data, and that

01:00:33.430 --> 01:00:36.450
was our baseline
mission, so I'm good--

01:00:36.450 --> 01:00:39.060
but it was a disappointment.

01:00:39.060 --> 01:00:43.060
But the engineers at Ball
Aerospace were very clever.

01:00:43.060 --> 01:00:45.430
And what they did
was they recognized

01:00:45.430 --> 01:00:47.520
that there is an axis
of symmetry built

01:00:47.520 --> 01:00:50.410
into the spacecraft itself.

01:00:50.410 --> 01:00:53.030
And so-- well, let me
back up for a second.

01:00:53.030 --> 01:00:58.270
What is it out in space that
make the telescope spin?

01:00:58.270 --> 01:01:01.310
The answer is radiation
pressure from the Sun.

01:01:01.310 --> 01:01:04.550
So you're literally
being pushed on by light.

01:01:04.550 --> 01:01:08.260
It's very small,
but it accumulates.

01:01:08.260 --> 01:01:10.340
So they recognized
that they could

01:01:10.340 --> 01:01:14.280
utilize this axis of
symmetry if they lined it

01:01:14.280 --> 01:01:17.160
up with the vector pointing
towards the radiation

01:01:17.160 --> 01:01:20.210
pressure towards the Sun,
and they did that perfectly.

01:01:20.210 --> 01:01:23.650
It would be like pointing
a boat directly upstream.

01:01:23.650 --> 01:01:26.760
If you balanced it, you would
neither yaw to the right

01:01:26.760 --> 01:01:29.530
nor to the left-- you
would stay the course.

01:01:29.530 --> 01:01:31.530
And that's what they did.

01:01:31.530 --> 01:01:37.370
So that axis of symmetry happens
to be in an orientation that

01:01:37.370 --> 01:01:41.240
puts the telescope observing
along the ecliptic plane

01:01:41.240 --> 01:01:43.540
of the solar system.

01:01:43.540 --> 01:01:45.750
So it limited the
amount of places

01:01:45.750 --> 01:01:47.690
where we could
point and observe.

01:01:47.690 --> 01:01:50.110
It also meant that we could
not point the telescope

01:01:50.110 --> 01:01:54.780
to the baseline patch of
sky that we were observing,

01:01:54.780 --> 01:01:57.230
but it actually opened
up the possibility

01:01:57.230 --> 01:01:59.700
of this whole entire
new thing called

01:01:59.700 --> 01:02:02.280
K2, which is Kepler's
second mission

01:02:02.280 --> 01:02:05.880
but actually named
after the mountain, K2.

01:02:05.880 --> 01:02:10.150
And so K2 is looking
at these patches of sky

01:02:10.150 --> 01:02:12.250
along the ecliptic,
and you see it there

01:02:12.250 --> 01:02:15.680
traced out as this
sine wave with regards

01:02:15.680 --> 01:02:18.340
to the plane of the
galaxy, which you see there

01:02:18.340 --> 01:02:21.150
as a flat image
across the screen.

01:02:21.150 --> 01:02:24.210
So it's going to observe each
of these patches of sky--

01:02:24.210 --> 01:02:27.830
it's been doing that
already for over a year now

01:02:27.830 --> 01:02:30.150
with great success.

01:02:30.150 --> 01:02:34.390
So it's kind of like a step and
stare approach, more like TESS.

01:02:34.390 --> 01:02:37.260
And we're finding lots of
planets in these patches,

01:02:37.260 --> 01:02:41.530
including some planets that
are-- oh, that pink part just

01:02:41.530 --> 01:02:43.940
shows you where
in the sky we get

01:02:43.940 --> 01:02:47.050
to look relative to the
Kepler field of view

01:02:47.050 --> 01:02:48.700
during the baseline mission.

01:02:48.700 --> 01:02:51.580
When you add up all the fields
that we will observe over

01:02:51.580 --> 01:02:56.540
a few years, maybe four years,
that adds up to about 4%

01:02:56.540 --> 01:03:00.400
of the sky instead of 0.25%.

01:03:00.400 --> 01:03:03.080
So it's great, and we're finding
planets that are actually

01:03:03.080 --> 01:03:06.210
really close by, like this
three-planet system that's

01:03:06.210 --> 01:03:08.290
just 100 light-years away.

01:03:08.290 --> 01:03:09.450
So it's doing good stuff.

01:03:09.450 --> 01:03:11.074
And I think it's
actually going to find

01:03:11.074 --> 01:03:14.410
some really good candidates for
the James Webb Space Telescope

01:03:14.410 --> 01:03:17.799
to observe when it
launches in 2018.

01:03:17.799 --> 01:03:20.090
AUDIENCE: How long is the
mission expected to continue?

01:03:20.090 --> 01:03:23.510
NATALIE BATALHA: How long
is it expected to last?

01:03:23.510 --> 01:03:28.030
So there is a hard constraint,
and that's the fuel.

01:03:28.030 --> 01:03:30.890
There's a fuel on board
the spacecraft that

01:03:30.890 --> 01:03:35.020
does some thruster firings to
change position, and that does

01:03:35.020 --> 01:03:36.970
have a finite lifetime.

01:03:36.970 --> 01:03:40.190
But I think it'll
easily last four

01:03:40.190 --> 01:03:43.030
years in this configuration.

01:03:43.030 --> 01:03:45.255
AUDIENCE: So this is
obviously a lot of data

01:03:45.255 --> 01:03:46.260
you guys are collecting.

01:03:46.260 --> 01:03:46.660
How much [INAUDIBLE]?

01:03:46.660 --> 01:03:48.910
NATALIE BATALHA: How much
data is left to be analyzed?

01:03:51.560 --> 01:03:53.170
We're still actually
even working

01:03:53.170 --> 01:03:55.500
on the data from the baseline
mission-- that first four

01:03:55.500 --> 01:03:59.460
years between 2009 and
2013-- because we're

01:03:59.460 --> 01:04:02.300
improving the pipeline
that does the analysis.

01:04:02.300 --> 01:04:06.240
So we'll get some more
discoveries from that data.

01:04:06.240 --> 01:04:07.760
But we're wrapping that up.

01:04:07.760 --> 01:04:10.640
That's due to finish
by September of 2017.

01:04:10.640 --> 01:04:13.400
So we've got about a
little less than two years

01:04:13.400 --> 01:04:15.490
to finish up the
analysis of that data.

01:04:15.490 --> 01:04:16.180
That's sad.

01:04:16.180 --> 01:04:18.070
The data sits in
the public archives,

01:04:18.070 --> 01:04:21.650
and scientists will be analyzing
